ariants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Keynes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Caines  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Caines","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Cahaignes in Eure, France, or Cahaynes in Calvados, France, both probably named with a Celtic element meaning ‘juniper bush’."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":1,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":11,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh de Keynes was born in 1095, in Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, England, his father, Kahannes de Keynes Lord, was 30 and his mother, Adelaide de Keynes, was 31. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1170, in his hometown, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1095–1170":"1095–1170","1145–1195":"1145–1195","1065–1131":"1065–1131","1106":"1106","ABT 1131":"umbes 1131","1145":"1145","1131":"1131","1065":"1065","1096":"1096","1195":"1195","1095":"1095","1170":"1170","Barton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, England":"Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1095–1170":"1095–1170","1145–1195":"1145–1195","1065–1131":"1065–1131","1106":"1106","ABT 1131":"noin 1131","1145":"1145","1131":"1131","1065":"1065","1096":"1096","1195":"1195","1095":"1095","1170":"1170","Barton, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, England":"Earls Barton, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"1095–1170":"1095–1170","1145–1195":"1145–1195","1065–1131":"1065–1131","1106":"1106","ABT 1131":"environ 1131","1145":"1145","1131":"1131","1065":"1065","1096":"1096","1195":"1195","1095":"1095","1170":"1170","Barton